{
  "answer": "**Old English 'mod' paradigmatically connotes the resilient inner seat of spirit, courage, and resolve amid trial—often a heroic firmness of will that steels against fear, sorrow, or storm.**[^1]\n\nA prime line from Cynewulf's *Andreas* (Matthew, bound and blinded by cannibals, yet praising God):  \n*Ic to anum þe, middangeardes weard, mod staþolige, fæste fyrhþlufan*  \n(\"I to Thee alone, guardian of middle-earth, [my] *mod* firm, fast heart-love\").[^2]\n\n**Urdu 'dil' paradigmatically names the intimate, shadowed core of feeling—yearning, pain, divine secrets, and love's hidden dwellers.**[^3]\n\nA prime line from Allama Iqbal's *Bang-e-Dara* (\"Jinhein main dhoondta tha\"):  \n*Woh nikle mere zulmat-khana-e-*dil* ke makeenon mein*  \n(\"They emerged as dwellers in the shadowed chamber of my *dil*\").[^4]\n\n**No substitution works without loss.** 'Mod' into the Urdu line yields a stoic \"mind-chamber\" (firm resolve, but flat, cerebral—stripping emotional intimacy and mystical secrecy). 'Dil' into the OE line yields a fervent \"heart firm\" (feeling's loyalty, but soft, vulnerable—diluting heroic, battle-ready courage amid torment). Each thrives in its idiom: *mod* the unyielding spirit of the exile/warrior; *dil* love's veiled ache.[^5]\n\n[^1]: Cynewulf, *Andreas*, [Chapter 1 (translation)](/works/cynewulf-andreas-07b573/01/translation/).\n[^2]: Cynewulf, *Andreas*, [p-da0c5e](/works/cynewulf-andreas-07b573/01/transliteration/#p-992aeb).\n[^3]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, [Chapter 4 (translation)](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/04-jinhein-main-dhoondta-tha-aasmanon-mein-zameenon-m/translation/).\n[^4]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, [p-fc632c](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/04-jinhein-main-dhoondta-tha-aasmanon-mein-zameenon-m/transliteration/#p-fc632c).\n[^5]: Unknown, *Old English Elegies*, [Chapter 6 (Maxims I, translation)](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/06-maxims-i/translation/) (for *mod*'s breadth); cf. Iqbal passim for *dil*'s emotive arc.",
